# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1998-german-federal-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Federal elections were held in all the 38 states of the German Confederation on 1 May 1848 to elect members of a new National Assembly known as the Frankfurt Parliament.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The ballot was not secret, and elected 585 members, mostly from the middle class.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The Pre-Parliament (*Vorparlement*) convened in the Paulskirche in Frankfurt on 31 March 1848 and ended on 30 May 1849.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Most of the 521 members of it were from South and West Germany, including 2 from Austria.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] There were 141 representatives from Prussia, of which 100 were from the Rhineland with a strong liberal tradition.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The Pre-Parliament dispersed on 3 April having appointed a committee of 50.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The radicals Friedrich Hecker and Gustav Struve were excluded as they had walked out; they had favored the abolition of both hereditary monarchy and standing armies, and a Federal constitution on North American lines.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The rebuffed Hecker proclaimed the German Republic in Baden on 12 April, but the so-called *Heckenputsch* failed within a week.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Hecker escaped to Switzerland and became a farmer in the United States.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Later Struve also went into exile (in Switzerland and the United States) before returning to Germany.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The Pre-Parliament had favoured universal suffrage, although individual states set their own qualifications.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] While Austria, Prussia and Schleswig-Holstein imposed no restrictions, farm hands were excluded in Baden and Saxony.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Bavaria and Wutternberg excluded domestic servants and workers, and Bavaria included only those paying direct taxation.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The Pre-Parliament set the ratio of one deputy to the National Assembly per 50,000 inhabitants of the German Confederation, totaling 649 deputies.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] However, Czech-majority constituencies in Bohemia and Moravia boycotted the election, reducing the total to 585.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Those elected included 157 judges and lawyers, 138 high officials, over a hundred university and high school teachers, and about 40 merchants and industrialists.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] Most of the 90 members of the nobility were in the learned professions, and there was only one peasant and four *handwerkers* (skilled artisans or craftsmen).
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1848-german-federal-election] The Frankfurt Parliament convened on 18 May at Frankfurt, when the members walked in solemn procession to the Paulskirche accompanied by the roar of cannon and the ringing of bells.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] Elections to the Zollparlament of the German Zollverein were held in February and March 1868.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] The Zollparlament consisted of the members of the Reichstag of the North German Confederation and members from the South German states.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] Those South German members were elected in these elections, the North Germans were the Reichstag members elected the previous year.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] In total, 85 South Germans were elected: 48 from Bavaria, 14 from Baden, six from Hesse-Darmstadt (additionally to the three Reichstag members in the province of Upper Hesse), and 17 from Württemberg.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] Most of the South German Zollparlament members were anti-Prussian regionalists.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1868-zollparlament-election] The outcome of the elections did not encourage Bismarck to take advantage of the Zollparlament as a vehicle for the politician unification of Germany.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] A federal election for the first Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 3 March 1871, 45 days after the founding of the Empire.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The voting took place under the provisions of the short-lived Constitution of the German Confederation.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] With certain limitations, all German males over 25 years of age were eligible to vote.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The National Liberal Party, one of the key supporters of the German unification of 1871, emerged as the largest party in the Reichstag.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The newly founded Catholic Centre Party came in second.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Reichstag approved the new Constitution of the German Empire on 14 April 1871.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] It set the legislative period at three years, putting the next election in 1874.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] At the end of the Austro-Prussian War of 1866, the victorious Kingdom of Prussia annexed many of the smaller north German states to form the North German Confederation.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The North German Constitution, which reflected the political ideas of Prussian minister president Otto von Bismarck, included a Reichstag elected according to equal, secret and universal manhood suffrage.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] With minor modifications, the North German Constitution became the Constitution of the German Confederation on 1 January 1871, during the final days of the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Confederation's 297-member Reichstag, last elected in August 1867, was expanded by 85 seats to accommodate the four south German states (Baden, Hesse south of the Main River, Württemberg and Bavaria) that were joining the Confederation to form what would become the German Empire on 18 January.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The election was held under general, equal, direct and secret suffrage.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] All German males over the age of 25 years were able to vote except for active members of the military and recipients of poor relief.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The restrictions on the military were meant to keep it from becoming politicized, while men on relief were considered to be open to political manipulation.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The constitutional guarantee of a secret vote was not safeguarded at the time, since ballot boxes and polling booths were not introduced until 1903.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] If no candidate in a district won an absolute majority of the votes, a runoff election was held between the first- and second-place finishers.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] It was possible for a replacement candidate to be introduced in a runoff.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] It was common at the time for individuals to campaign not as a member of a specific party but rather under a more general label such as liberal, conservative, clerical or particularist.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Once the parliament met, such members would join an existing party or work with like-minded representatives to form a new one.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] As a result, the picture of a new Reichstag's party makeup would come into focus only some time after the voting.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Liberalism, supported primarily by the middle class, was the leading political movement at the time of the Empire's foundation.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] It was divided into two large ideological groups, the liberal left, of which the German Progress Party (DFP) was the largest party, and national liberalism, centered in the National Liberal Party (NLP).
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Both parties had supported Bismarck's unification policies, although the NLP was more consistent in its backing of the Chancellor.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The two main conservative parties were the German Conservative Party and the German Reich Party.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] They backed Bismarck and found their primary support among the nobility and large landowners in the eastern states.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Catholic Centre Party was founded following the election for the Prussian House of Representatives in November 1870.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] On 23 March 1871, a group of Catholic members of the newly elected Reichstag came together to form a Centre Party parliamentary caucus.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The party's membership was almost exclusively Catholic and, unlike most parties of the time, spanned the full range of social classes.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Centre's party program for 1871, entitled "Justice is the basis of governance", promised to protect the federal nature of the Empire and strive for the "constitutional establishment of guarantees of the civic and religious freedom of all citizens".
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Imperial Liberal Party formed after the 1871 election as a liberal-conservative offshoot of the National Liberal Party.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] It was a party of notables (*Honoratiorenpartei*) that supported Bismarck, rejected parliamentarization and sought to work with both the National Liberals and the Conservative Party.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Workers Party (SDAP) had favored a greater German unification (one which would have included Austria) and during the Franco-Prussian War had advocated "proletarian internationalism".
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] In its founding Eisenach Program of 1869, the party promised to fight for the abolition of class rule, elimination of the capitalist mode of production, a standard working day, and the prohibition of child labor.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Polish Party represented the approximately three million German citizens whose native language was Polish.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Most of them lived in the Prussian provinces of Posen, West Prussia and Silesia.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The parties that supported Bismarck's policies, notably on unification, became the dominant parties in the new Reichstag: the National Liberals, Centre, Conservatives and Progress Party.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Voter turnout was just 51%, the lowest during the life of the Empire.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Historian Volker Ullrich suggests that the lack of voter interest was due to the fact that the initial enthusiasm over the founding of the Empire remained limited primarily to the national-liberal bourgeoisie.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The changes in the results from the previous Reichstag (shown below) are a combination of two previous elections: to the North German Reichstag in 1867 and to the *Zollparlament*, the parliament of the German Customs Union (*Zollverein*), in 1868.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The *Zollparlament* consisted of all members of the North German Reichstag plus 85 representatives elected from the south German states that joined the German Empire in 1871.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] They received as many seats in the new Reichstag as they had held in the *Zollparlament*.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The first meeting of the imperial Reichstag, whose provisional home was the Prussian House of Representatives, took place in the White Hall of the Berlin Palace, the residence of the kings and emperors of Prussia.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] Emperor Wilhelm I chose to welcome the Reichstag members there because he did not want to give the impression that he had his subjects to thank for the crown.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The throne of the Holy Roman Emperor Henry III had been brought from Goslar for the occasion, and the victorious Prussian generals, led by Helmuth von Moltke, carried the imperial regalia.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The Reichstag approved the new Constitution of the German Empire with just seven 'no' votes on 14 April 1871.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] In one other significant vote, taken on 11 March 1872, the Reichstag replaced church with state supervision of German schools.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1871-german-federal-election] The next election was held on 10 January 1874 in accordance with the constitutional three-year term of office for Reichstag members.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] A federal election for the second Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 10 January 1874.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The National Liberal Party remained the largest party in the Reichstag, with 147 of the 397 seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The Centre Party, which had campaigned against the anti-Catholic laws introduced by the government of Chancellor Otto von Bismarck*,* was able to double its vote total from the previous election and placed second.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The Conservative and Imperial Liberal parties lost the most seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The most significant political event to affect the 1874 election was the start in July 1871 of the *Kulturkampf* (Cultural Struggle), an attempt to suppress the political power of Catholicism in Germany.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Chancellor Otto von Bismarck feared that Catholics' loyalty lay more with the Vatican than Germany, and many liberals saw the Catholic Church as politically reactionary.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Although the majority of the anti-Catholic laws affected only Prussia, they were nevertheless a major concern for all German Catholics since Prussia accounted for about two-thirds of the German population.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] One of Bismarck's chief goals in the *Kulturkampf* was to break the Catholic Centre Party.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Catholics made up about one-third of both Prussia's and the Empire's population, and the Centre Party, which had been founded only in December 1870, had placed second in the 1871 election with 58 seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Catholics were most heavily concentrated in the Imperial Territory of Alsace–Lorraine, which had just been won from France in the Franco-Prussian War, in Bavaria, Baden, and the Prussian provinces of Rhineland, Westphalia and heavily Polish Posen.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The major gainers in the 1874 election were the National Liberal Party and the Centre Party; losses affected primarily the Conservative Party and the short-lived Imperial Liberal Party.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Rather than suppressing the Catholic vote, the *Kulturkampf* served to consolidate political Catholicism.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] The Centre Party more than doubled the number votes it had received in 1871, from just under 708,000 to over 1.4 million.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] It was the most votes of any party, although the Centre won 56 fewer seats than the National Liberals.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] Such a result was possible under the Empire's electoral system if a party was more successful at winning majorities in individual districts and/or won more runoff elections.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] There were 46 runoffs for the 397 seats in 1874.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] 1874 was the first year that representatives from Alsace–Lorraine were elected to the Reichstag.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1874-german-federal-election] All 15 opposed the German annexation of the region.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] A federal election for the third Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 10 January 1877.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] It was a regularly scheduled election based on the three-year legislative period established in the imperial constitution.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The voting was strongly influenced by the economic downturn that had followed the Panic of 1873.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The sharp economic downturn that began in late 1873 significantly affected the 1877 Reichstag election.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] Known in Germany as the "founders' crash" (*Gründerkrach*) because it followed the period of rapid growth after the founding of the Empire in 1871, the worldwide Panic of 1873 triggered an economic depression that lasted until 1879 in Germany.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] Particularly hard hit were workers who lost their jobs and members of the middle class who relied on income from stocks.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The economic problems caused Chancellor Otto von Bismarck to shift away from the free trade policies supported by the National Liberals, who were the largest party in the Reichstag.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] In an early reaction to his policy changes, Rudolph von Delbrück, head of the Reich Chancellery and a strong proponent of free trade, resigned in 1876.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The same year saw the founding of the German Conservative Party, which supported protectionism and endorsed Bismarck's overall policies.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The hardships that the working class faced because of the founders' crash led to a strengthened sense of solidarity among them that was reflected in the SAPD's showing in the 1877 election.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The election overall was favorable to Bismarck.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The German Conservative Party gained 19 seats, the liberal-conservative German Reich Party 6 and the Socialist Workers' Party 3.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] In spite of losing 20 seats, the National Liberals remained the largest party in the Reichstag.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The other major loser was the liberal German Progress Party, down 14 seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] The new Löwe-Berger Group, which had split from them in 1874, won 9 seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1877-german-federal-election] After two assassination attempts against Emperor Wilhelm I in May and June 1878 and disputes over the planned Anti-Socialist Law that Bismarck introduced as a result, the third Reichstag was dissolved by the Emperor at Bismarck's request, and a new election was held on 30 July 1878.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] A federal election for the fourth Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 30 July 1878.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] It took place 18 months ahead of schedule after two unsuccessful assassination attempts against Emperor Wilhelm I led Chancellor Otto von Bismarck to request an early dissolution of the Reichstag that had been elected in January 1877.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Bismarck tried to tie the attacks on the Emperor to the Social Democrats and, indirectly, the National Liberals in order to weaken them and strengthen the conservative parties.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Although the National Liberals lost 30 seats and the two main conservative parties gained 38, the National Liberals remained the strongest party in the Reichstag.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] It went on to pass Bismarck's harsh Anti-Socialist Law in October 1878.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The 1878 election, held just 18 months after the previous Reichstag election, is often referred to as the "assassination-attempt election" (*Attentatswahl*) because it was wholly dominated by the two unsuccessful attempts to assassinate Emperor Wilhelm I in the spring of 1878.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Chancellor Otto von Bismarck took immediate political advantage of the public outrage to attack both the leftist Socialist Workers' Party (the forerunner of the Social Democratic Party, or SPD) and the centrist National Liberals.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] On 20 May Bismarck presented a draft "Law on the Defence Against Social Democratic Outrages" (*Gesetz zur Abwehr sozialdemokratischer Ausschreitungen*), which the Reichstag rejected by a vote of 251 to 57.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The law's wording was so broad that the National Liberals feared that it could be directed against them.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Bismarck had in fact expected that the party, which in 1876 had blocked a bill he had introduced to extend the range of politically criminal acts, would oppose the measure and that he could then brand them as accomplices of the social democrats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The second assassination attempt on 2 June was committed by a man named Karl Nobiling who was suffering under "personal delusions".
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] On the following morning, the Wolff semi-official news agency reported that Nobiling had confessed to having SPD sympathies.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] It was all but impossible that he could have done so, however, because he had been badly wounded during the attack and was not capable of responding to questions.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Bismarck nevertheless used the situation to dissolve the Reichstag on 11 June.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Some historians see evidence connecting Bismarck's ministry to Wolff's report and say that it marked the start of the campaign to link Social Democrats to the act and accuse the National Liberals of collusion with them.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] In the campaign for the new Reichstag, the majority of the National Liberals' candidates came from its conservative wing and had already committed themselves to voting for Bismarck's proposed anti-socialist law.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Even some politicians from the left-of-center German Progress Party moved towards the Chancellor.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] One flyer it put out declared that "the social democratic fraud, along with its parasitic plants, is a disgrace to the entire German people".
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The Social Democrats for their part were severely hampered in their ability to campaign.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Although no restrictive laws had yet been passed, prominent social democrats had their houses searched and papers confiscated.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The party was forced to restrict its campaigning to electoral districts in which it already had a dominant position.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] As Bismarck had hoped, conservative parties were the clear winners in the election.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Both the German Reich Party (also known as the Free Conservative Party) and the German Conservative Party picked up 19 seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The National Liberals lost 30 seats but with 97 remained the strongest party in the Reichstag.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] In spite of the attacks against it, the Socialist Workers' Party (Social Democrats) lost just four seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Turnout was 63%, only slightly higher than the previous two elections.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] On 19 October 1878, Bismarck's Anti-Socialist Law passed the new Reichstag 221 to 149.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] All National Liberals voted for the law, as did the members of the two conservative parties, while those from the German Progress Party, the Catholic Centre Party – which had been the object of Bismarck's anti-Catholic *Kulturkampf* – and the Socialist Workers' Party voted against it.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] The law prohibited societies, meetings, publications, public festivities and processions that "aim[ed] at the overthrow of the existing political or social order through social-democratic, socialist or communist endeavors".
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] It also banned collecting or appealing for contributions to support such activities.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] Emperor Wilhelm I signed the law on 21 October 1878.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1878-german-federal-election] It was subsequently renewed 4 times before it was allowed to expire on 30 September 1890, after Bismarck had resigned as chancellor.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] A federal election for the fifth Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 27 October 1881.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] It was a regularly scheduled election under the Reichstag's three-year terms of office.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The dominant issues were protective tariffs and the government's requests for increased taxes.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The conservative parties, which supported the government, lost seats, leaving the Reichstag without options for a stable majority.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] As a result, Chancellor Otto von Bismarck was unable to realize many of his plans in the new parliament.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Taxes and tariffs were the dominant issue in the 1881 election.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Increasing competition from abroad had led to the passage of protective tariffs on agricultural and industrial goods in 1879.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The Catholic Centre Party, German Conservative Party and 27 out of 97 members of the National Liberal Party voted for the tariff bill, while the Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the remainder of the National Liberals opposed it.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The differences of opinion within the National Liberal Party led to a group of members from its left wing splitting off and forming the Liberal Union in 1880.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] In spite of the income from tariffs, the government needed additional revenue to cover its expenses.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] In the autumn of 1880, the Reichstag approved a seven-year budget for the military, but a majority resisted the additional tax increases that the government later requested.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Chancellor Otto von Bismarck hoped that the election of 1881 would improve the chances of passing his tax package.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The parties that Bismarck generally relied on for votes lost seats in the election.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The Centre, Conservatives and German Reich Party (Free Conservatives) together had 177 seats, down 33 from the previous election and well short of the 199 needed for a majority.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Opposite the conservative grouping stood the Liberal Union and German Progress Party with 106 seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] They and the National Liberal Party with its 45 seats formed a *Kartell* with the aim of coming to a mutual understanding before critical votes.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The share of the vote going to the Social Democratic Party (officially still named the Socialist Workers' Party) dropped by just 1.5% despite the harsh restrictions placed on it by the Anti-Socialist Law in 1878.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The number of seats it won in the Reichstag actually rose, from 9 to 13.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Because he lacked a majority in the Reichstag, Bismarck's only choices were to try to put together temporary blocs that would support him or to rule without parliament.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] His attempts to do the latter ran into opposition from both his advisors and the Reichstag, which refused to grant him the necessary funds.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] As a result, many of Bismarck's post-election reform plans had to be shelved.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Emperor Wilhelm I was so unhappy about how little the SPD's share of the vote had decreased that he sent a note to the Reichstag saying that the government would hold to its tax and tariff policies even against the Reichstag's opposition.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] He also issued a decree to public officials requiring them to advocate the government's positions.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] Bismarck came to realize that he needed to change course and try to win over the socialists.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] In November 1881, he announced a bill to provide workers with insurance against accident, illness, disability and old age.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The corresponding laws began to go into effect in 1883.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1881-german-federal-election] The Anti-Socialist Law remained in effect until 1890.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 1998 to elect the members of the 14th Bundestag.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Party (SPD) emerged as the largest faction in parliament for the first time since 1972, with its leader Gerhard Schröder becoming chancellor.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The Christian Democrats had their worst election result since 1949.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Since German reunification on 3 October 1990, the unemployment rate in Germany had risen from 4.2% to 9.4% in 1998, with the Federal Labor Office registering more than 4 million unemployed.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The unified Germany had to fight economic and domestic difficulties even as it actively participated in the project of European integration.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Most people blamed the centre-right coalition government of the Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union (CDU/CSU) and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) for the economic difficulties.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Longtime Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government was regarded by many as not having fully implemented the unification after eight years, in view of the mass protests in many eastern German towns due to job losses and social welfare cuts.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The 1998 campaign began with both the CDU and SPD working out who would lead their parties.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] There had been rumours that Kohl would resign and allow Wolfgang Schäuble to take the reins of the CDU, but these rumours were rendered obsolete when Kohl announced in April 1997 that he would seek the chancellorship for a sixth term.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The two contenders for the SPD nomination were Oskar Lafontaine, the party's chairman, and Gerhard Schröder, Minister-President of Lower Saxony.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] On 1 March 1998, Schröder led the SPD to a huge victory in the Lower Saxony state election, gaining an unusual absolute majority for the second time and effectively receiving the SPD nomination for federal chancellor.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Schröder had announced he would withdraw his bid for the nomination if he received below 42 percent of the popular vote.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] In the 1998 general elections, Schröder received 47.9 percent.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Following this election, Lafontaine withdrew his bid and Schröder was inaugurated in the May 1998 convention.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] For the SPD, Schröder offered a new face for the party.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] He gave the party a new vigor, one that was lacking in the CDU after Kohl proclaimed his nomination.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Many in the CDU questioned if Kohl had made the right choice for the party.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU campaign was based on the experience and reputation of Kohl.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] One of the CDU's main slogans was 'Safety, not Risks.' "Kohl exploited his familiarity and experience, as well as his status as Europe's longest serving head of government." The SPD on the other hand ran the campaign using strategies developed in the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD set up election headquarters and introduced 'rapid rebuttal units' not unlike those used by Bill Clinton of the United States in his successful presidential bid in 1992.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD avoided direct attacks at Kohl, but rather focused on their message of a "new center".
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The FDP had usually ridden on the coattails of the CDU, and was mostly disapproved in the polls.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] With the SPD well ahead in the polls, many of the voters from the CDU had fewer incentives to vote for the FDP.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The FDP was also having trouble projecting a coherent platform to voters.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The Greens too were having issues concerning their platform.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The two factions in the Greens, the fundamentalists and the pragmatists, had problems settling on their platform since the founding of the Green party.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The major issue of the 1998 campaign was unemployment.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] In 1996, the unemployment rate in Germany surpassed the government's "limit" of 4 million unemployed people.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Both parties blamed high labor costs, high taxes and the high welfare costs as the causes of the problem.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] During the campaign, Schröder used this issue against Kohl, calling him 'the unemployment chancellor.' Unemployment was worst in the former East Germany.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] While the national rate stood at 9.4 percent, former East Germany was suffering with unemployment at 20 percent.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Many in the former East Germany blamed Kohl for the slow economic recovery.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Another issue at hand were Germany's tax and welfare reforms.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] While the CDU/CSU had offered proposals to reduce benefits in healthcare and pensions, the SPD controlled Bundesrat secured the passage of the bill.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The proposed bill also offered tax cuts that were to benefit the rich, something the SPD opposed.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] While Kohl continually pushed the issue of European integration, the issue fell short from voters' minds.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Schröder, on the other hand, almost ignored the issue.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Many voters in Germany had other concerns besides the European Union.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Toward the end of the campaign, polls placed the CDU/CSU and FDP coalition in a tie with the SPD and Green coalition.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Despite these polls, the final numbers told a different story.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD-Green coalition won an unexpectedly large victory, taking 345 seats and earning a strong majority in the Bundestag—the first centre-left absolute majority in post-World War II Germany.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD won 40.9 percent of the vote, due to an increase of 4.5 percent from 1994.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU-FDP coalition had gone into the election with a solid majority and 341 seats, but was cut down to 288 seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU lost 6.2% of its 1994 vote, and lost 109 electoral districts to the SPD.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Germany's mixed-member proportional system, in which a slate of statewide delegates are elected alongside the electorate delegates, softened the blow somewhat, so the CDU/CSU only suffered a net loss of 49 seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] It was still the CDU/CSU's worst defeat ever.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] By contrast, their junior coalition partner, the FDP, netted a loss of just 4 seats.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD swept all single-member constituency seats in the states of Brandenburg, Saxony-Anhalt, Saarland, Bremen, Hamburg and (for the first and last time) Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Kohl lost his own constituency of Ludwigshafen, though he was still re-elected to the Bundestag through the Rhineland-Palatinate CDU party list, and he had not won the seat in the 1983 and 1987 elections.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Future Chancellor Angela Merkel only narrowly won her constituency of Stralsund – Rügen – Grimmen with only 37.3 percent of the vote; the only time she got less than 40 percent of the vote.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] A new government was formed by a coalition between the SPD and the Greens, with the SPD's Gerhard Schröder as chancellor and Greens leader Joschka Fischer as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] It was the first red-green coalition government at the federal level in Germany, as well as the first purely centre-left government in post-World War II Germany.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Kohl stepped down as chairman of the CDU, as did CSU chairman Theodor Waigel.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] The 1998 German election was historic in many ways.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] It resulted in a centre-right government being succeeded by a left-wing one—the first in postwar Germany (the SPD's previous term in government had been at the helm of a centre-left coalition).
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] In addition, it brought to an end the sixteen-year rule of Kohl – the second-longest of any German chancellor, and the longest tenure for a democratically elected head of government in German history.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] It has been compared to the defeat of Winston Churchill in 1945 – both were seen as conservative wartime leaders, and in both cases both were turned out of office by the electorate once the war was over.
[src:1998-german-federal-election/1998-german-federal-election] Churchill was ousted before World War II was even over, while Kohl managed to hang onto power for two more terms after the reunification of Germany (which is often considered to be the end of the Cold War).
